c"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"thematicBreak","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"USBEBsFlFW"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"🟢 Station 1 - In Folds We Trust...","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"SqIyytI8Yq"}],"identifier":"id-station-1-in-folds-we-trust","label":"🟢 Station 1 - In Folds We Trust...","html_id":"id-station-1-in-folds-we-trust","implicit":true,"key":"LqYp2oBigF"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Machine learning models need data for learning but also for model evaluation. In limited data scenarios,  K-Fold cross-validation is economical as it enables using all the data for training and also to reuse all of it for validation. In the words of scikit-learn: “In k-fold CV, the training set is split into k smaller sets. The following procedure is followed for each of the k “folds”. A model is trained using k-1 of the folds as training data; the resulting model is validated on the remaining part of the data (i.e., it is used as a test set to compute a performance measure such as accuracy). The performance measure reported by k-fold cross-validation is then the average of the values computed in the loop.” You can see the visualization of k-fold from scikit-learn on the left in the image below.","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"fDue8vicsg"}],"key":"WUbhqGTUCo"},{"type":"image","url":"/build/k-fold-b02c9b27dbdf8ae0562859d4b7359db7.png","alt":"Caption","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"CtOlIjbyNB","urlSource":"../images/k-fold.png"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"T